This statement is symptomatic of the strangeness that `girth` is `ENat`-valued while `diam` is `Nat`-valued. I think we should rename the current `girth` to `egirth` and define a new `Nat`-valued `girth`, so that your statement becomes `G.egirth ≤ 2 * G.ediam + 1` and `G.girth ≤ 2 * G.diam + 1`.
Thank you for the review, I've created #13910 to do this!

```suggestion
lemma nonempty_of_diam_ne_zero (h : G.diam ≠ 0) : Nonempty α := by
```
```suggestion
lemma diam_ne_zero_nonempty (h : G.diam ≠ 0) : Nonempty α := by
```

I know it's private, but might as well name it properly
```suggestion
private lemma diam_eq_zero_of_not_bddAbove (h : ¬BddAbove {d | ∃ u v, d = G.dist u v}) :
```

```suggestion
lemma exists_dist_eq_diam [Nonempty α] : ∃ u v, G.dist u v = G.diam := by
```

```suggestion
@[simp] lemma diam_bot : (⊥ : SimpleGraph α).diam = 0 := by
```
Can we also have
```
@[simp] lemma diam_top [Nonempty α] : (⊤ : SimpleGraph α).diam = 1 := by
```
and
```
@[simp] lemma diam_eq_one [Nonempty α] : G.diam = 1 ↔ G = ⊤ := by
```
What about the complete graph on one vertex in `diam_top` and `diam_eq_one`? Is there an instance instead of `[Nonempty α]` that removes that case?
Nontrivial, I guess

```suggestion
lemma dist_le_diam (h : G.diam ≠ 0) : ∀ u v, G.dist u v ≤ G.diam := by
```

It might be worth having a `FiniteDiam` predicate saying `G ≠ ⊥ ∧ BddAbove {d | ∃ u v, d = G.dist u v}`, then show that `G.FiniteDiam ↔ G.diam ≠ 0` (or `G.FiniteDiam ↔ G.ediam ≠ ⊤` and rename your lemmas so that we can use dot notation on `FiniteDiam`
Do you think this idea still works well with the new implementation?

```suggestion
lemma diam_mono [Nonempty α] (hg : G.Connected) (hz : G.diam ≠ 0) (h : G ≤ G') :
```
There seems to be something wrong with your definition: A disconnected graph will have diameter the maximum of the diameter of its components instead of `0` since `G.dist` has junk value `0`

... and similarly here the e-diam of a disconnected graph will be the maximum of the e-diam of its components instead of being infinite.

I think the correct definition is
```suggestion
/--
The extended diameter is the greatest distance between any two vertices, with the value `⊤` in
case the distances are not bounded above.
-/
noncomputable def ediam (G : SimpleGraph α) : ℕ∞ := ⨆ u v, G.edist u v
```
where `G.dist u v = (G.edist u v).toNat`. Then
```
noncomputable def diam (G : SimpleGraph α) : ℕ∞ := G.ediam.toNat
```
will be the correct notion

That's a good point, sorry about that! 
We don't have `edist` yet, but it is mentioned in the TODO list of `Metric.lean` [here](https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/blob/b83d79b9b7e4cddba1c6c27829a053ecb88e1f08/Mathlib/Combinatorics/SimpleGraph/Metric.lean#L26). Should I define it and prove its needed lemmas in a separate PR?
Yes, that would be great!

Does this approach seem good? There is still a lot of work do be done (I've marked the PR as WIP), but I would like to check that I'm not building the API on wrong foundations. Also I would love to hear @b-mehta's opinion on this.
Yeah I think Yaël's suggestion is the right one
I didn't mean to imply that Yaël's isn't right, instead, I'm wondering if this type of proofs using the weird `ediam_def` are okay. Sorry for the ambiguous question!

Then this will be 
```suggestion
lemma edist_le_ediam {u v : α} : G.edist u v ≤ G.ediam := by
```
etc

```suggestion
This module defines the diameter of a simple graph, which measures the maximum distance between
```
Let's add the type of this for readability
Let's make the contrapositive a lemma: G.ediam = 0 under the assumption [IsEmpty \a]
Hmm `convert_to` is often a sign there's an API lemma missing. Doesn't `ediam_def` help a little?

```suggestion
case the distances are not bounded above, or the graph is not connected.
```
Can you tag `not_nonempty_iff` with `push_neg`? Then you shouldn't need this line anymore
I'm getting an "unknown attribute" error
Oh maybe the attribute is just simp
It has a simp attribute already
I am confused. Can you ask on Zulip?

The lemmas are hard-coded to the tactic, [this](https://leanprover.zulipchat.com/#narrow/stream/113489-new-members/topic/Is.20there.20a.20push_neg.20attribute.3F) is the Zulip topic.
We are not using that lemma here anymore, do you want me to try adding it, `not_nontrivial_iff_subsingleton`, and `not_subsingleton_iff_nontrivial`, perhaps in a separate PR?
Yes, that sounds like a plan! Thanks

```suggestion
      exact (Set.range_nonempty _).csSup_mem (Set.finite_range _)
```

```suggestion
  huv ▸ (edist_le_subgraph_edist h).trans edist_le_ediam
```
Same here

```suggestion
lemma ediam_eq_zero_of_subsingleton [Subsingleton α] : G.ediam = 0 := by
```

```suggestion
lemma nontrivial_of_ediam_ne_zero (h : G.ediam ≠ 0) : Nontrivial α := by
```

The point of having this is that there are many lemmas in this API which require `Nonempty α` as a typeclass assumption, so I thought this would provide an easy way to have that.
I have turned `zero_lt_ediam_of_nontrivial` into an iff statement instead, what do you think?
Having it as an iff statement is good, but we should also have the alias for the nontrivial => ... and subsingleton => ... versions, where the assumption is a typeclass assumption
Well, typeclass search knows that `Nontrivial α` implies `Nonempty α`, so I don't really see the problem?
Ah, good to know! Working on it.
For clarity, I was replying to Rida's message above

```suggestion
lemma ediam_def : G.ediam = ⨆ p : α × α, G.edist p.1 p.2 := by
```

```suggestion
lemma edist_le_ediam {u v : α} : G.edist u v ≤ G.ediam := le_iSup₂ u v
```
In general, you should use `le_iSup_of_le` to chain, rather than `le_iSup`
This is not working, maybe because the types of the parameters at `le_iSup₂` are different from what we have here? But I've used `le_iSup_of_le` for chaining, thanks!
Ah sorry, `biSup_mono` is the lemma you want to be using here

It is not clear to me how it applies here. Maybe I'm misunderstanding something, but `biSup_mono` seems to be a comparison between two `iSup`s, and the second parameter seems to be of type `prop` which depends on the first parameter.

No, I was right. `le_iSup₂` is the correct lemma. Elaboration just seems to be weak
```suggestion
lemma edist_le_ediam {u v : α} : G.edist u v ≤ G.ediam := le_iSup₂ (f := G.edist) u v
```
Ah, this notation is new to me, thank you very much!

```suggestion
  rw [not_nontrivial_iff_subsingleton] at h
```
seems clearer

```suggestion
lemma ediam_ne_zero [Nontrivial α] : G.ediam ≠ 0 := by
```
since it's a typeclass assumption and `ediam_ne_zero_iff_nontrivial` also exists

Can we also have
```
lemma ediam_eq_top_of_not_preconnected (h : ¬G.Preconnected) : G.ediam = ⊤ := by
```

If `G'.diam = 0` then `G'.diam ≤ G.diam`
```suggestion
lemma diam_mono_of_ne_zero (h : G ≤ G') (hG : G.diam ≠ 0) :
```
So this lemma is useless

```suggestion
  · exact Or.inl ediam_eq_zero_of_subsingleton
```
You're missing the contraposite

If `G.diam = 0`, then you can take `u = v`.
```suggestion
lemma exists_dist_eq_diam_of_ne_zero [Nonempty α] :
    ∃ u v, G.dist u v = G.diam := by
```

Just FYI this can be written as
```suggestion
  · cases h <| IsEmpty.forall_iff.mpr trivial
```
or
```suggestion
  · simp [Preconnected] at h
```

You should stop thinking about the supremum as "either the maximum value of my function or infinity if my function is unbounded" and start thinking in terms of its universal property (which is usually all you need, really):
```suggestion
@[gcongr] lemma ediam_anti (h : G ≤ G') : G'.ediam ≤ G.ediam :=
  iSup₂_mono fun _ _ ↦ edist_le_subgraph_edist h
```
(btw `edist_le_subgraph_edist` should be called `edist_anti` and tagged `gcongr`, if you mind opening a PR!)

I'm surprised I didn't notice that the hypotheses aren't needed. Thank you for the tip! I will keep it in mind. It highlights how `noncomputable` definitions can be more powerful than computational ones (to me, the universal property feels `noncomputable`-like, as opposed to the former which feels more computational).
Yes, quite precisely!

Similarly here you worked too hard, probably because you overstrengthened `hn`
```suggestion
lemma diam_mono_of_ediam_ne_top (h : G ≤ G') (hn : G.ediam ≠ ⊤) : G'.diam ≤ G.diam :=
  ENat.toNat_le_toNat (ediam_mono h) hn
```

```suggestion
lemma diam_eq_zero_of_ediam_eq_top (h : G.ediam = ⊤) : G.diam = 0 := by
  rw [diam, h, ENat.toNat_top]

lemma ediam_ne_top_of_diam_ne_zero (h : G.diam ≠ 0) : G.ediam ≠ ⊤ :=
  mt diam_eq_zero_of_ediam_eq_top  h
```

```suggestion
lemma diam_anti_of_ediam_ne_top (h : G ≤ G') (hn : G.ediam ≠ ⊤) : G'.diam ≤ G.diam :=
```
Just quickly mentioning that maybe `Diam` instead of `Diameter` is descriptive enough for the filename

I think this is descriptive enough
```suggestion
lemma ediam_eq_top : G.ediam = ⊤ ↔ ∀ b < ⊤, ∃ u v, b < G.edist u v := by
```

These two are general lemma about `iSup` respectively on
* `ENat`
* a `CompleteLinearOrder`

Can you make sure their proofs are one-liners from the respective APIs?

I did the first one, I'm having trouble with the second one. Is the API of `CompleteLinearOrder` located in `Order/CompleteLattice`? If yes, then that file doesn't import `Finite`. Should I import it there?
Yes, should be fine

I've wrote the lemma in `ConditionallyCompleteLinearOrder` instead because it has the needed lemma `Nonempty.csSup_mem`, and because it is more general. However, I can't provide `iSup₂` version there because there is no `iSup_prod` lemmas. Is this fine for now? Another solution would be to move these lemmas to `CompleteLinearOrder`, but then work will need to be done to bring the equivalent of `Nonempty.csSup_mem` to there.
Yes indeed I think it's fine

```suggestion
lemma exists_dist_eq_diam [Nonempty α] :
```

```suggestion
lemma exists_eq_iSup₂_of_lt_top {ι₁ ι₂ : Type*} {f : ι₁ → ι₂ → ℕ∞} [Nonempty ι₁] [Nonempty ι₂]
```
Can we also have `exists_eq_iSup_of_lt_top`?
I'd be tempted to leave a comment here saying that neither of `Finite α` or `G.ediam ≠ ⊤` implies the other
We should add the other half of the universal property: if every edist is <= k, then the ediam is <= k as well. Similarly for diam
Actually, we should have the universal property as a lemma `ediam_le_iff : G.ediam \le k \iff \for u v, G.edist u v \le k`
Yeah that too!

theorem exists_eq_ciSup_of_finite [Nonempty ι] [Finite ι] {f : ι → α} : ∃ i, f i = ⨆ i, f i :=
  Nonempty.csSup_mem (range_nonempty f) (finite_range f)

theorem exists_eq_ciInf_of_finite [Nonempty ι] [Finite ι] {f : ι → α} : ∃ i, f i = ⨅ i, f i :=
